---
import Layout from '../../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import RelatedTools from '../../../components/RelatedTools.astro';

// Tool metadata
const name = "Screen Dead Pixel Test";
const category = "general";
const tier = "General Everyday Utilities";

// On-page SEO metadata
const pageTitle =
  "Screen Dead Pixel Test - Free Online Dead Pixel Checker & Tester";
const description =
  "Free online screen dead pixel test to check and find dead or stuck pixels on any monitor. Works as a dead pixel checker for Windows, Mac, 4K, iPhone, Android, NVIDIA & AMD displays.";
const canonicalUrl = "https://toolkify.app/tools/general/screen-dead-pixel";
const ogImage = "/og/screen-dead-pixel.png";
const keywords =
  "screen dead pixel test, dead pixel test, dead pixel checker, dead pixel test online, dead pixel test windows, dead pixel tester, check dead pixels, dead pixel check, find dead pixels, dead pixel monitor test, dead pixel test iphone, dead pixel android, dead pixel test 4k, dead pixel test mac, dead pixel test nvidia, dead pixel test amd, dead pixel test windows 10, dead pixel test app";
---

<Layout 
  title={pageTitle}
  description={description}
  toolName={name}
  toolCategory={category}
  keywords={keywords}
  canonical={canonicalUrl}
  ogImage={ogImage}
  ogType="website"
  hideBanner={true}
>
  <!-- SEO JSON-LD WebApplication Schema -->
  <script type="application/ld+json" is:inline>
    {
      "@context": "https://schema.org",
      "@type": "WebApplication",
      "name": "Screen Dead Pixel Test",
      "alternateName": "Dead Pixel Checker & Tester",
      "genre": "Utility",
      "url": "https://toolkify.app/tools/general/screen-dead-pixel",
      "description": "Free online screen dead pixel test to check, find, and identify dead or stuck pixels on any display using pure, full-screen color backgrounds. Works on Windows, Mac, 4K, iPhone, Android, NVIDIA and AMD monitors.",
      "applicationCategory": "UtilitiesApplication",
      "operatingSystem": "All",
      "browserRequirements": "Requires JavaScript. Requires HTML5.",
      "featureList": [
        "Dead pixel test with pure white, black, red, green and blue screens",
        "Dead pixel checker with custom hex color backgrounds",
        "Stuck pixel tester with subpixel magnifier zoom",
        "Auto-cycle mode for hands-free dead pixel checking",
        "Works as a dead pixel test for Windows, Mac, 4K, iPhone and Android",
        "100% private, client-side testing"
      ],
      "offers": {
        "@type": "Offer",
        "price": "0.00",
        "priceCurrency": "USD"
      }
    }
  </script>

  <!-- FAQ JSON-LD Schema -->
  <script type="application/ld+json" is:inline>
    {
      "@context": "https://schema.org",
      "@type": "FAQPage",
      "mainEntity": [
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is a dead pixel?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>A dead pixel is a single point on your screen that no longer produces light or color. Because its transistor has stopped receiving power, it stays permanently black regardless of what the display is showing. On an LCD or OLED panel, a dead pixel appears as a tiny dark dot that never changes, which makes it easiest to spot against a pure white background during a screen dead pixel test.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Why is there a dead pixel on my screen?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>A dead pixel usually appears because of a manufacturing defect, a broken transistor, or a loss of electrical connection to that part of the panel. Physical impact, pressure, heat, moisture, or simply age can all cause a pixel to stop working. Sometimes what looks like a dead pixel is actually a stuck pixel, so running a dead pixel test across several colors helps confirm which type you have.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What does a dead pixel look like?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>A dead pixel looks like a very small black or dark dot on the screen that stays the same no matter what image is displayed. It is most visible on bright, solid backgrounds such as pure white or light colors. Unlike a stuck pixel, which may glow red, green, or blue, a true dead pixel remains unlit during every color in a dead pixel test.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Can you fix a dead pixel?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>A true dead pixel is difficult to fix because the pixel receives no power at all, so software methods rarely revive it. Stuck pixels, however, can often be repaired using rapid color-cycling videos or gentle pressure techniques. If a genuine dead pixel remains after testing, the most reliable solution is a warranty replacement if the panel meets the manufacturer's dead pixel policy.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How to fix a dead pixel?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>To attempt a fix, first run a dead pixel test to confirm whether the pixel is dead or stuck. For stuck pixels, try a flashing pixel-fixer video that rapidly cycles colors on the affected area, or gently massage the spot with a soft, damp microfiber cloth (at your own risk). These methods can re-energize a stuck subpixel, but a fully dead pixel typically requires a professional repair or panel replacement.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What causes a dead pixel?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>Dead pixels are caused by a failure in the tiny transistor that controls the pixel's light output. Common causes include manufacturing imperfections, physical shock or pressure on the screen, exposure to extreme heat or cold, moisture damage, and general wear over the display's lifespan. Any of these can permanently cut power to a pixel, leaving it dark.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What does dead pixel mean?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>The term dead pixel means a picture element on a display that has completely stopped functioning and no longer emits any light or color. Each pixel is made of red, green, and blue subpixels; when all of them fail and remain off, the pixel is considered dead and shows up as a permanent black dot on the screen.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How does a dead pixel happen?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>A dead pixel happens when the transistor driving that pixel loses power or fails electrically. This can occur during manufacturing, from physical damage such as a drop or excessive pressure, or gradually as the panel ages and its components degrade. Once the connection is broken, the pixel can no longer switch on and stays permanently dark.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What does a dead pixel look like on a monitor?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>On a monitor, a dead pixel looks like a fixed black speck that does not move, blink, or change color as the screen content updates. It becomes obvious when you display a full-screen white or bright background using a dead pixel monitor test. If the dot instead glows a constant color, it is a stuck pixel rather than a dead one.</p>"
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  </script>

