          >
            <span>Why is there a dead pixel on my screen?</span>
            <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="w-4 h-4 text-stone group-hover:text-primary transition-transform duration-200 shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5">
              <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" />
            </svg>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-content hidden px-6 pb-5 pt-1 text-sm text-slate leading-relaxed border-t border-hairline-soft/30 bg-surface-soft/10">
            <p>A dead pixel usually appears because of a manufacturing defect, a broken transistor, or a loss of electrical connection to that part of the panel. Physical impact, pressure, heat, moisture, or simply age can all cause a pixel to stop working. Sometimes what looks like a dead pixel is actually a stuck pixel, so running a dead pixel test across several colors helps confirm which type you have.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- FAQ 3 -->
        <div class="faq-accordion-item group">
          <button
            type="button"
            class="faq-toggle-btn w-full text-left font-display font-medium text-[15px] sm:text-base text-primary flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer px-6 py-4.5 hover:bg-surface-soft transition-colors duration-200"
            aria-expanded="false"
          >
            <span>What does a dead pixel look like?</span>
            <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="w-4 h-4 text-stone group-hover:text-primary transition-transform duration-200 shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5">
              <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" />
            </svg>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-content hidden px-6 pb-5 pt-1 text-sm text-slate leading-relaxed border-t border-hairline-soft/30 bg-surface-soft/10">
            <p>A dead pixel looks like a very small black or dark dot on the screen that stays the same no matter what image is displayed. It is most visible on bright, solid backgrounds such as pure white or light colors. Unlike a stuck pixel, which may glow red, green, or blue, a true dead pixel remains unlit during every color in a dead pixel test.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- FAQ 4 -->
        <div class="faq-accordion-item group">
          <button
            type="button"
            class="faq-toggle-btn w-full text-left font-display font-medium text-[15px] sm:text-base text-primary flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer px-6 py-4.5 hover:bg-surface-soft transition-colors duration-200"
            aria-expanded="false"
          >
            <span>Can you fix a dead pixel?</span>
            <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="w-4 h-4 text-stone group-hover:text-primary transition-transform duration-200 shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5">
              <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" />
            </svg>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-content hidden px-6 pb-5 pt-1 text-sm text-slate leading-relaxed border-t border-hairline-soft/30 bg-surface-soft/10">
            <p>A true dead pixel is difficult to fix because the pixel receives no power at all, so software methods rarely revive it. Stuck pixels, however, can often be repaired using rapid color-cycling videos or gentle pressure techniques. If a genuine dead pixel remains after testing, the most reliable solution is a warranty replacement if the panel meets the manufacturer's dead pixel policy.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- FAQ 5 -->
        <div class="faq-accordion-item group">
          <button
            type="button"
            class="faq-toggle-btn w-full text-left font-display font-medium text-[15px] sm:text-base text-primary flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer px-6 py-4.5 hover:bg-surface-soft transition-colors duration-200"
            aria-expanded="false"
          >
            <span>How to fix a dead pixel?</span>
            <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="w-4 h-4 text-stone group-hover:text-primary transition-transform duration-200 shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5">
              <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" />
            </svg>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-content hidden px-6 pb-5 pt-1 text-sm text-slate leading-relaxed border-t border-hairline-soft/30 bg-surface-soft/10">
            <p>To attempt a fix, first run a dead pixel test to confirm whether the pixel is dead or stuck. For stuck pixels, try a flashing pixel-fixer video that rapidly cycles colors on the affected area, or gently massage the spot with a soft, damp microfiber cloth (at your own risk). These methods can re-energize a stuck subpixel, but a fully dead pixel typically requires a professional repair or panel replacement.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- FAQ 6 -->
        <div class="faq-accordion-item group">
          <button
            type="button"
            class="faq-toggle-btn w-full text-left font-display font-medium text-[15px] sm:text-base text-primary flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer px-6 py-4.5 hover:bg-surface-soft transition-colors duration-200"
            aria-expanded="false"
          >
            <span>What causes a dead pixel?</span>
            <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="w-4 h-4 text-stone group-hover:text-primary transition-transform duration-200 shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5">
              <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" />
            </svg>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-content hidden px-6 pb-5 pt-1 text-sm text-slate leading-relaxed border-t border-hairline-soft/30 bg-surface-soft/10">
            <p>Dead pixels are caused by a failure in the tiny transistor that controls the pixel's light output. Common causes include manufacturing imperfections, physical shock or pressure on the screen, exposure to extreme heat or cold, moisture damage, and general wear over the display's lifespan. Any of these can permanently cut power to a pixel, leaving it dark.</p>
          </div>
