            aria-expanded="false"
          >
            <span>How does a dead pixel happen?</span>
            <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="w-4 h-4 text-stone group-hover:text-primary transition-transform duration-200 shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5">
              <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" />
            </svg>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-content hidden px-6 pb-5 pt-1 text-sm text-slate leading-relaxed border-t border-hairline-soft/30 bg-surface-soft/10">
            <p>A dead pixel happens when the transistor driving that pixel loses power or fails electrically. This can occur during manufacturing, from physical damage such as a drop or excessive pressure, or gradually as the panel ages and its components degrade. Once the connection is broken, the pixel can no longer switch on and stays permanently dark.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- FAQ 9 -->
        <div class="faq-accordion-item group">
          <button
            type="button"
            class="faq-toggle-btn w-full text-left font-display font-medium text-[15px] sm:text-base text-primary flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer px-6 py-4.5 hover:bg-surface-soft transition-colors duration-200"
            aria-expanded="false"
          >
            <span>What does a dead pixel look like on a monitor?</span>
            <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="w-4 h-4 text-stone group-hover:text-primary transition-transform duration-200 shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5">
              <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" />
